comment: This software is great, but I am experiencing two tragic flaw which limits its utility. Now, I should preface this with the statement that this issue may be with my VoIP provider, and I intend to file a bug report. The first flaw is that the app doesn't always restart if it closes unexpectedly -- this means that if it closes, I have no way to tell if my phone is offline without looking to see if the app is running. The second is that often it says that my phone is registered with my provider, but will not accept calls (implying that it is not actually connected). I have to disconnect and re-connect with my provider to  accept incoming calls. Even when looking at the phone, it's impossible to know if I am connected to my provider or not! These flaws make the program very frustrating to use. Ideally, once registered (assuming I have an internet connection), the phone will ring whenever someone calls. This is sadly not the case, and I miss a fair share of calls as a result. With these problems resolved, I would give this app 5 stars and gladly pay/donate for it. Since this is a crucial app for me, these flaws are more than a small inconvenience.

But, being a typical (East) Indian I didn't want to spend money on that. :D So, I googled and found "callcentric". After a few incantations, the daemon called callcentric granted me my wish and gave me a VoIP number. But, the problem was I had never used a VoIP number till then! :D So, I checked with callcentric support and they suggested this app.  Configuring the app was a piece of cake. Instructions from Callcentric support also helped.  Once the app was setup, I called my callcentric number from my regular mobile ... and this softphone on my tablet started buzzing (but not ringing) right next to me!! How cool is that? :)  Please be aware that this app can be set to be "always on", or to be on only in the presence of wifi, or be on only for outgoing calls. The app clearly states that  "always on" will drain the battery. Since I don't expect anyone to be calling me much on my callcentric number I have set it to "be on only for outgoing calls".  (I also installed codecs that come in a separate app, although I am not sure I needed them.)

CSipSimple has probably 5 times the amount of options of that other client, but it seems not as resilient(which in my case is far more important than having a thousand options). The issue is mostly with roaming between access points; what I've always experienced with the SCCP client is that roaming between two access points didn't require the client to re-register to the phone system.. but this doesn't seem the case with CSipSimple. It seems like a small issue, but if you use your cell phone also as a "cordless" to have your extension with you while in meetings or walking around the office.. then it becomes a problem: instead of just staying registered like the old client, CSipSimple seems to unregister immediately and then it takes a long time to re-register (or sometimes it doesn't re-register at all) creating long windows in which my extension just leaves the phone and cannot be reached.
